re, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1350–":"1350–Afdød","1350–Female":"1350–Afdød","1343–1400":"1343–1400","–1400":"–1400","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1327–1374":"1327–1374","1330–1396":"1330–1396","1327":"1327","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","BEF 1368":"1368","1350":"1350","1417":"1417","Chillington, Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chillington, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1350–":"1350–Overleden","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","1343–1400":"1343–1400","–1400":"–1400","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1327–1374":"1327–1374","1330–1396":"1330–1396","1327":"1327","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","BEF 1368":"1368","1350":"1350","1417":"1417","Chillington, Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chillington, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1350–":"1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1343–1400":"1343–1400","–1400":"–1400","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1327–1374":"1327–1374","1330–1396":"1330–1396","1327":"1327","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","BEF 1368":"1368","1350":"1350","1417":"1417","Chillington, Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chillington, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitmore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitmoor (Devon) or Whitmore (Staffordshire and Dorset), or from any of numerous other places in England with names denoting a white moor or mere (from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ or <i>mere</i> ‘pool’).","History: Francis Whitmore settled in Cambridge, MA, before 1648."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitemore","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Whitmore  ."]},{"name":"Whittemore","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): variant of   Whitmore  .","History: Thomas Whittemore came from England to Charlestown, MA, in or <i>c.</i> 1639. Amos Whittemore, born in Cambridge, MA, in 1759 was an inventor and gunsmith, and another Thomas Whittemore was born in Boston in 1800; he was a Universalist clergyman and MA legislator."]},{"name":"Whitmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitmore  .","Americanized form of German   Wittmeyer   or of   Wittmer  ."]},{"name":"Whitmarsh","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitemarsh, a place in the parish of Sedgehill, Wiltshire, named from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ (i.e. ‘phosphorescent’) + <i>mersc</i> ‘marsh’. Compare   Whitmore  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Whitmore was born in 1350, in Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Whitmore, was 23 and her mother, Cicely de Claveley, was 20. She married Sir John Giffard. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1350–":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1343–1400":"1343–1400","–1400":"–1400","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1327–1374":"1327–1374","1330–1396":"1330–1396","1327":"1327","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1343":"1343","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","BEF 1368":"1368","1350":"1350","1417":"1417","Chillington, Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chillington, Staffordshire, England":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"}